### TITLE ###
IfBranchesCollapseStrEnumArms
### DESCRIPTION ###
If/else over a string-enum discriminant should join back into the
original enum at the bottom, not a union-of-single-value-enums.
This is the Phase 4 regression for "StrEnum fragmentation."
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: ["a", "b", "c"]):
    if x == "a":
        log = "AAA"
    else:
        if x == "b":
            log = "BBB"
        else:
            log = "CCC"
    after = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> ["a", "b", "c"]
  log @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:12 -> ["b", "c"]
  log @ 6:13 -> <no-type>
  log @ 8:13 -> <no-type>
  after @ 9:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 9:13 -> ["a", "b", "c"]

# Symbol types
  after (local): ["a", "b", "c"]
  f (fn): <no-type>
  log (local): str
  x (param): ["a", "b", "c"]

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
IfElseUnionCollapsesIntAndOptionalInt
### DESCRIPTION ###
The most common narrowing pattern: `if x != null: ... else: ...`
where x has declared type int?. Branches contribute int (truthy)
and int? (else falls through to base). The union collapse should
land at int? (since int <: int?).
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        log = "ok"
    else:
        log = "fail"
    after = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  log @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  log @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  after @ 6:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 6:13 -> int?

# Symbol types
  after (local): int?
  f (fn): <no-type>
  log (local): str
  x (param): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
SwitchPeelsAndJoinsBackToEnum
### DESCRIPTION ###
Switch exhausts a closed enum; post-switch the discriminant joins
back to the original enum (each case narrowed to a single value,
the join collapses them).
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: ["a", "b", "c"]):
    switch x:
        case "a":
            log = 1
        case "b":
            log = 2
        case "c":
            log = 3
    after = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:12 -> ["a", "b", "c"]
  log @ 4:13 -> <no-type>
  log @ 6:13 -> <no-type>
  log @ 8:13 -> <no-type>
  after @ 9:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 9:13 -> ["a", "b", "c"]

# Symbol types
  after (local): ["a", "b", "c"]
  f (fn): <no-type>
  log (local): int
  x (param): ["a", "b", "c"]

# Diagnostics
  (none)
